PASS 1 review — criterion G1G2 (edit-set / scope accuracy). Structured coaching output below.

```json
{
  "criteria_reviewed": ["G1G2"],
  "affirmations": [
    {
      "criteria": ["G1G2"],
      "note": "No hallucinated edit targets — every artifact the plan names resolves to real source/docs: the in-use `claim` (open->in_progress) path is `src/rebar/_commands/transition.py::claim_compute` -> `_plan_review_precheck` (transition.py:634-695) -> `txn.claim_core` (txn.py:331); the fast local check is `rebar.llm.plan_review.attest.claim_gate_check` (attest.py:66); the signature scheme is `src/rebar/signing.py` with `SIGNATURE` a KNOWN_EVENT_TYPE; the `REVIEW_RESULT` sidecar is reducer-IGNORED + fsck-recognised via `_NON_REPLAY_KNOWN_TYPES` (src/rebar/reducer/_version.py:44); and the 'TAG_DELTA/event-rollout note' to cross-check is real (src/rebar/reducer/_version.py:31-37 + docs/event-schema.md:71,91-97)."
    },
    {
      "criteria": ["G1G2"],
      "note": "Behavioral hunks are correctly low blast-radius and the in-scope runtime change (the blocking claim-path gate) ALREADY shipped (transition.py:634-695, default OFF). As written the ACs require docs + a regression test + (at most) re-documenting an existing flag — no out-of-scope CREATION of new runtime behavior is demanded, so high-blast-radius is not a concern here."
    }
  ],
  "findings": [
    {
      "criteria": ["G1G2"],
      "location": "Scope (all three bullets) + Acceptance Criteria AC1/AC2/AC3",
      "evidence": [
        "ABSENCE: the plan describes behaviors ('disable-the-gate config', 'rollback/back-out path', 'deploy-ordering doc', 'spec references this design') but never names the concrete FILES/SYMBOLS it will create or edit (config.py? a new docs/*.md? docs/plan-review-gate.md? docs/event-schema.md? the 5fd2 ticket body?).",
        "Without a named edit target per scope bullet, the consumers/callers a change would touch cannot be enumerated for review (the core of G1G2)."
      ],
      "checklist_item": "- [ ] Name the concrete edit target(s) for each Scope bullet (which config key/file for the disable flag, which doc path for the rollback runbook + deploy-ordering writeup, where the 5fd2 reference goes) so edit-set accuracy and consumer impact can be verified.",
      "suggested_fix": ""
    },
    {
      "criteria": ["G1G2"],
      "location": "Acceptance Criteria AC1 ('A config flag disables the plan-review gate so `claim` is unchanged (fail-open) when off; covered by a test.')",
      "evidence": [
        "The disable flag the AC proposes ALREADY EXISTS as a real edit target/consumer: `verify.require_plan_review_for_claim: bool = False` (src/rebar/config.py:260), default OFF.",
        "Its claim-path consumer already short-circuits when off: `_plan_review_precheck` returns None (allow, claim unchanged) at transition.py:661-662, and fails OPEN on unreadable config at transition.py:652-660; rebar.toml:14-21 + docs/plan-review-gate.md:180 both state 'Turning it off is the rollback.'",
        "AC1's 'covered by a test' is already satisfied: tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_plan_review_gate.py:69-72 (`test_gate_off_by_default_claims_without_attestation`) and :233-239 (config True/False load) exercise exactly this."
      ],
      "checklist_item": "- [ ] Clarify whether AC1 introduces a NEW config flag or is the existing `verify.require_plan_review_for_claim` (config.py:260); if the latter, re-scope AC1 to 'verify/document the existing flag + its fail-open test' to avoid a duplicate-flag edit set and an unenumerated second consumer of the claim path.",
      "suggested_fix": "Reword AC1 to reference the existing `verify.require_plan_review_for_claim` flag (config.py:260) and its consumer `_plan_review_precheck` (transition.py:661-662), scoping the deliverable to a characterization test rather than a new kill-switch."
    },
    {
      "criteria": ["G1G2"],
      "location": "Scope bullets 2-3 + AC2 (old/new coexistence + deploy-ordering for the REVIEW_RESULT sidecar + signature events)",
      "evidence": [
        "The coexistence/deploy-ordering edit target the plan treats as new is an ALREADY-SHIPPED consumer set: REVIEW_RESULT is in `_NON_REPLAY_KNOWN_TYPES` (reducer/_version.py:44) so older clones preserve-and-ignore it; the rollout-ordering convention ('upgrade reconciler-running clones first') already lives at docs/event-schema.md:91-97; the parent epic's own comment (1782271126…) records child db7b shipped 'REVIEW_RESULT + attestation events follow rebar's preserved-and-ignored-by-older-clones rollout (fsck WARN; reconcile hosts upgrade first).'",
        "So AC2's deploy-ordering/coexistence half points at an existing source of truth; authoring a parallel one risks divergence rather than filling a gap."
      ],
      "checklist_item": "- [ ] Reconcile AC2's old/new-coexistence + deploy-ordering with the existing artifacts (reducer/_version.py:44, docs/event-schema.md:91-97, the db7b rollout note) — cross-reference/extend them as the named edit target rather than creating a divergent second convention; if a genuine residual gap remains (e.g. the SIGNATURE head-state event vs an old reducer), name it specifically.",
      "suggested_fix": ""
    },
    {
      "criteria": ["G1G2"],
      "location": "Acceptance Criteria AC3 ('The epic 5fd2 spec references this rollout/rollback design')",
      "evidence": [
        "AC3 names an edit target ('the epic 5fd2 spec') without its location/kind: the authoritative spec is the rebar ticket body 5fd2-a7c2-0aec-48fa (not a tracked file), so 'reference it' is an under-specified edit target.",
        "The 5fd2 spec ALREADY contains this design: Success Criteria #4 states 'a config PREFERENCE that turns the plan-review requirement ON/OFF … DEFAULTS OFF … rollback is simply turning the preference off — an ordinary config preference, not a deploy-time kill-switch, and no separate rollback mechanism is needed', and the prior epic comment already records the db7b cross-clone coexistence handling."
      ],
      "checklist_item": "- [ ] Specify WHERE/HOW the 5fd2 spec is to be edited (ticket comment vs description block) and reconcile AC3 with the fact that 5fd2 Success Criteria #4 already documents the disable=rollback design — i.e. state what NEW text AC3 adds rather than re-asserting an existing reference.",
      "suggested_fix": ""
    }
  ]
}
